{{for|the river of West Asia|Khabur (Euphrates)}} {{Use dmy dates|date=July 2013}} '''Abora''' is the name of an ancestal solar deity of [[La Palma]] ([[Canary Islands]]) and a traditional god of the [[Guanches]], and of two [[reed boat]]s.
==Supreme being==
Abora ('''Ibru'''<ref>{{cite book |last=Garrison Brinton |first=Daniel |title=Races and Peoples: Lectures on the Science of Ethnography |url= |year=1901 |publisher=D. McKay |location= |language= |isbn= |oclc= |doi= |id= |pages=122 |chapter= |chapterurl= |quote= }}</ref>) is the name of the [[God|supreme being]] of the religion of the [[Guanches]] on the island of [[La Palma]].<ref>{{Cite EB1911|wstitle=Guanches|volume=12|pages=650-651}}</ref><ref name="Hodgson1844">{{cite book|author=William Brown Hodgson|title=Notes on Northern Africa, the Sahara and Soudan: In Relation to the Ethnography, Languages, History, Political and Social Condition, of the Nations of Those Countries|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=cQwOAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA104|year=1844|publisher=Wiley and Putnam|pages=104–|authormask=|trans-title=|format=|origyear=|oclc=|doi=|bibcode=|id=|quote=|laysummary=|laydate=}}</ref> In Guanche mythology of the island of [[Tenerife]], the supreme god was called [[Achamán]].
==''Abora'', reed boat== {|{{Infobox ship begin}} {{Infobox ship image | Ship image = Expedioner.jpg | Ship caption = ''Abora'' project display and Dominique Goerlitz }} {{Infobox ship career | Hide header = yes | Ship country = | Ship flag = | Ship name = ''Abora'' | Ship owner = | Ship ordered = | Ship builder = [[Aymara ethnic group|Aymara Indians]], Huatajata, [[Lake Titicaca]], Bolivia | Ship original cost = | Ship laid down = | Ship launched = | Ship acquired = | Ship commissioned = | Ship decommissioned = | Ship in service = | Ship out of service = | Ship renamed = | Ship struck = | Ship reinstated = | Ship honours = | Ship captured = | Ship fate = | Ship status = | Ship notes = }} {{Infobox ship characteristics | Hide header = | Header caption = | Ship class = [[Totora (plant)|Totora]] [[reed boat]] | Ship tons burthen = | Ship length = {{convert|32.8|ft|abbr=on}} | Ship beam = | Ship draught = | Ship draft = | Ship hold depth = | Ship propulsion = | Ship sail plan = [[Square rig]] with [[bipod mast]], [[steering oar]], and [[leeboard]]s<ref>{{Cite web | last = Allen | first = J M | title = ''Abora III'' building and history | work = | publisher = | date = | url = http://www.atlantisbolivia.org/aboraIIIbuildingandhistory.htm | doi = | accessdate = 23 April 2010}}</ref> | Ship complement = | Ship armament = | Ship notes = }} |}
''Abora'' was a Bolivian-made reed boat, designed in 2002, to travel more than {{convert|450|nmi|mi km|0}} between Egypt, Lebanon and Cyprus.<ref>[http://archives.cnn.com/2002/WORLD/sailing/06/19/ancient.ppl/ The Abora project] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080921142716/http://archives.cnn.com/2002/WORLD/sailing/06/19/ancient.ppl/ |date=21 September 2008 }} CNN</ref> This was an attempt to prove a theory that there were no boundaries to the travels of ancient sailors, defying modern estimations of limited exploration by prehistoric man. The idea was inspired by Norwegian explorer [[Thor Heyerdahl]], who sailed from South America to [[Polynesia]] on the [[Kon-Tiki]] balsa raft in 1947.
==''Abora III''==
A similar boat, the Abora III, was launched in 2007 for a [[transatlantic crossing]]. Due to damage from several storms, the expedition was abandoned {{convert|550|mi|nmi km|0}} away from the [[Azores]].<ref>[http://abora3.com/english/diary.html ''Abora III'' Diary] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110707074713/http://abora3.com/english/diary.html |date=7 July 2011 }} Abora III Diary</ref>
