{{bilateral|Comoran-North Korean|Comoros|North Korea}}

'''Comoros–North Korea relations''' ({{lang-ko|코모로-조선민주주의인민공화국 관계}}) refers to the [[bilateralism|current and historical relationship]] between the [[Comoros]] and the [[North Korea|Democratic People's Republic of Korea]] (DPRK), commonly known as North Korea. Neither nation maintains an embassy in their respective capitals. Formerly the DPRK had an ambassador stationed in [[Moroni, Comoros|Moroni]].<ref name="Ambassador">{{cite book |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=North Korea Quarterly |volume=10-13 |publisher=Institute of Asian Affairs |page=5 |date=1977 }}</ref>

==History==
Diplomatic relations with North Korea were established soon after the Comoros gained its independence from [[France]] on 6 July 1975, on 13 November later that year.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ncnk.org/resources/publications/NCNK_Issue_Brief_DPRK_Diplomatic_Relations.pdf |title=DPRK Diplomatic Relations |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=2015 |website=www.ncnk.org |publisher=National Committee on North Korea |access-date=29 July 2015 |page=4 }}</ref> This was during the rule of Prince [[Said Mohamed Jaffar]], who had replaced President [[Ahmed Abdallah]] in a coup only months before. He himself was replaced in January 1976 by  [[Ali Soilih]], a revolutionary [[Islamic socialism|Islamic socialist]] and anti-colonialist. Soilih, in addition to implementing radical reforms, established close connections with many of the [[Cold War]] states in the habit of aiding revolutionary movements. Among these were North Korea, which established an embassy in the Comoros within a year. On 18 January 1977, the first ambassador So Jinyong presented his credentials to Vice President Mohamed Hassan Ali, and made a visit to President Soilih.<ref name="Ambassador"/>

The [[Maoism|Maoist]]-inspired leader, whose [[Red Guards (China)|Red Guard]]-esque militia and other armed forces received training from the left-wing [[Tanzania]]n regime of [[Julius Nyerere]], also received some degree of aid from the North Koreans.<ref>{{cite book |editor-last=Bunge |editor-first=Frederica M.|date=1982 |title=Indian Ocean, five island countries |publisher=[[United States Department of the Army]] |page=179}}</ref> On 15 March 1978, the North Korean ambassador presented a gift from [[Kim Il-sung]] to President Soilih, in response to which the Comoros expressed its "full support and firm solidarity with the Korean people's struggle" to achieve an independent and peaceful [[Korean reunification]].<ref>{{cite book |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Summary of World Broadcasts: Far East, Part 3  |location=[[London]] |publisher=[[BBC|British Broadcasting Corporation]] |date=1978}}</ref>

Only two months after this event Soilih was ousted and killed in a coup by French mercenaries, which reinstalled the former President Ahmed Abdallah. Abdallah's rule was strictly anti-communist, and on 3 December 1983 the Comoros became the only African state to break off diplomatic relations with the DPRK following the [[Rangoon bombing]], when on 9 October that year the North Koreans attempted to assassinate the [[South Korea]]n military ruler [[Chun Doo-hwan]] during a visit to [[Burma]].<ref>{{cite book |last1=Drachkovitch |first1=Milorad M. |last2=Gann |first2=Lewis H. |title=[[Yearbook on International Communist Affairs]] |publisher=[[Hoover Institution]] |page=242 |date=1984 |isbn=0817980318 }}</ref> For the remainder of his time in office, Abdallah maintained close relations with South Korea, visiting [[Seoul]] in 1987.<ref>{{cite book |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |volume=16, 1-26 |title=Korea News Review |location=[[Seoul]] |publisher=''[[The Korea Herald]]'' |page=104 |date=1987 }}</ref> Relations resumed in the 1990s, with the end of Abdallah's government in 1989, replaced by a long series of likewise unstable regimes.<ref>{{cite book |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Daily Report: East Asia |publisher=[[NewsBank]] |page=81 |date=1996 |volume=18}}</ref>

