==Date==
===Present===
Dates are usually written in "day month year" (DMY) order. This order is used in both the all-numeric date (for example "{{lang|ru|28.08.17}}") and the expanded form (for example "{{lang|ru|28 августа 2017 г.}}"). Single-digit numbers for day or month may have a preceding nought (for example "{{lang|ru|28.08.2017}}"), but omitting it (for example "{{lang|ru|28.8.2017}}") is more usual.

When saying the date, it is usually pronounced using the ordinal number of the day first, then the month (for example "{{lang|ru|Двадцать восьмое августа}}").

===Historical===

Russia used the [[Byzantine calendar]] up to 1700, the [[Julian calendar]] between 1700 and 1918, and the [[Gregorian calendar]] since 1918.  Until the final years of [[Peter the Great]] in the early 1720s, Russia used [[Cyrillic numerals]] to denote dates on coins.  Thus, for example, СИ (208) denoted 7208 [[Anno Domini|AM]] (September 1, 1699 through August 31, 1700 [[Old Style and New Style dates|OS]]) and ҂АѰ (1700) denoted [[Anno Domini|AD]] 1700 OS.

==Time==
The [[12-hour clock|12-hour notation]] is often used in the spoken language. The [[24-hour clock|24-hour notation]] is used in writing, with a colon as the standardised and recommended separator (e.g. “{{lang|ru|9:07}}”).

