{{Infobox monument | name = Ezana Stone | native_name = | image = EzanaGreekTablet.jpg | caption = The Ezana Stone | location = [[Kingdom of Aksum]] | type = [[stele]] | material = | length = | width = | height = | begin = | complete = | dedicated_to = King [[Ezana of Axum|Ezana]] | map_image = | map_text = | map_width = | coordinates = | website = }}
The '''Ezana Stone''' is a [[stele]] from the ancient [[Kingdom of Aksum]]. The [[Aksumite architecture|stone monument]] documents the conversion of [[Ezana of Axum|King Ezana]] to [[Christianity]] and his conquest of various neighboring areas, including [[Meroë]].
From AD 330 to 356, King Ezana ruled the ancient Kingdom of Aksum centered in the [[Horn of Africa]]. He fought against the [[Nubians]], and commemorated his victories on stone tablets in praise of [[God]]. These liturgical epigraphs were written in various ancient languages, including the Ethiopian Semitic [[Ge'ez language|Ge'ez]], the South Arabian [[Sabaean language|Sabaean]], and [[Ancient Greek|Greek]]. The king's [[engraving]]s in stone provided a trilingual monument in different languages, similar to the [[Rosetta stone]].
The [[Ethiopian Orthodox Tewahedo Church]] had its beginnings during this period. [[Tyrannius Rufinus|Rufinus]]'s ''Ecclesiastical History'' narrates that [[Saint Frumentius]], a slave and tutor for the very young King, converted him to [[Christianity]]. Towards the end of his reign, King Ezana launched a campaign against the [[Cush (Bible)|Kushites]] around 350 which brought down the [[Kingdom of Kush]]. Various stone inscriptions written in Ge'ez (using the [[Ge'ez alphabet|Ge'ez script]]) have been found at Meroë, the central city of the Kushites.
