{{Infobox book | <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject_Novels or Wikipedia:WikiProject_Books --> | name = Showdown | title_orig = | translator = | image = ShowdownNovel.jpg | caption = First edition | author = [[Errol Flynn]] | cover_artist = | country = Australia | language = English | series = | genre = [[Adventure novel]] | publisher = [[Invincible Press]] | release_date = 1946 | media_type = Print ([[Hardcover|Hardback]] & [[Paperback]]) | pages = | preceded_by = | followed_by = }}
'''''Showdown''''' is a romantic [[adventure novel]] written by famous [[Tasmania]]n-born actor [[Errol Flynn]] (1909&ndash;1959). It was first published in 1946 by Invincible Press (Australia) and subsequently in the UK in 1952 and in paperback in 1961. Flynn draws on his experiences working in and around [[New Guinea]] when young to provide the background. Accounts of his sailing in New Guinea waters appear in his autobiographies, ''Beam Ends'' (1937) and ''[[My Wicked, Wicked Ways]]'' (1959). The novel is dedicated to German-American artist [[John Decker (artist)|John Decker]], who painted Flynn's [[portrait]], translated in the same year to Spanish as ''Un drama en los Mares del Sur'' (Renacimiento, 1946).
==Background== The novel was originally called ''One Man in His Time'' and then ''Charlie Bow Tie Proceeds''.<ref>TOWN CALLED HOLLYWOOD: Heaven Help Flynn! He's Written a Book Scheuer, Philip K. Los Angeles Times (1923-Current File) [Los Angeles, Calif] 18 July 1943: C3.</ref>
While writing it he was also reported to be working on another book, a novel about the nephew of [[Moctezuma II|Montezuma]] fighting the Conquistadores, called ''Cuautenos''.<ref>DRAMA AND FILM: Warners May Produce Two Novels by Flynn Cagney's Forthcoming Picture Titled 'Johnny Come Lately;' Asther Assigned Schallert, Edwin. Los Angeles Times (1923-Current File) [Los Angeles, Calif] 01 May 1943: 7.</ref>
