'''Ukodo''' is a yam and unripe [[Plantain (cooking)|plantain]] dish of the [[Urhobo people]] of Nigeria. <ref>[http://cookingncleaning.blogspot.com/2013/05/ukodo-pepper-soup-porridge-urhobo.html Nigerian Urhobo Ukodo (pepper soup Yam pottage)] 18 May 2013 Sapele Honey</ref> The [[Itsekiri people]] of the Niger Delta also make a similar dish called Epuru. It is essentially a pottage, a stew of meat and vegetable with its base as the Nigerian pepper soup.

It is sometimes cooked with lemon grass and potash.<ref name="Ekeh2005">{{cite book|author=Peter Palmer Ekeh|title=Studies in Urhobo Culture|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=jjeNIESBArkC&pg=PA496|date=January 2005|publisher=Urhobo Historical Society|isbn=978-978-067-769-5|pages=496–}}</ref> 

It is usually used for marriage and bural ceremonies or as breakfast, particularly during the cold season. <ref name="Lim2016">{{cite book|author=T. K. Lim|title=Edible Medicinal and Non-Medicinal Plants: Volume 10, Modified Stems, Roots, Bulbs|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=tUCFCwAAQBAJ&pg=PA293|date=2 February 2016|publisher=Springer|isbn=978-94-017-7276-1|pages=293–}}</ref>

A poem by the Nigerian Chovwe Inisiagho-Ogbe describes both the ingredients and the process of cooking Ukodo in a light-hearted way.<ref name="Ekeh2005">{{cite book|author=Peter Palmer Ekeh|title=Studies in Urhobo Culture|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=jjeNIESBArkC&pg=PA496|date=January 2005|publisher=Urhobo Historical Society|isbn=978-978-067-769-5|pages=496–}}</ref>

